{{Infobox language |name=Bzyb |nativename=бзыҧ |states=[[Turkey]], ''[[Abkhazia]]'' |region=[[Bzyb River]] |speakers=? |familycolor=Caucasian |fam1=[[Northwest Caucasian languages|Northwest Caucasian]] |fam2=[[Abazgi language|Abazgi]] |fam3=[[Abkhaz language|Abkhaz]] |isoexception=dialect |glotto=bzyb1238 |glottorefname=Bzyb |notice=IPA }}
'''Bzyb''' (also spelled '''Bzyp''') is a major dialect of [[Abkhaz language|Abkhaz]], native to the [[Bzyb River]] region of [[Caucasus]].<ref name=EB>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-first=Dale H. |editor-last=Hoiberg|encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Britannica |title=Abkhaz|edition = 15th |year=2010|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica Inc. |volume=I: A-ak Bayes |location=Chicago, Illinois |isbn=978-1-59339-837-8|pages=33}}</ref>
It differs from standard Abkhaz mainly in terms of [[phonology]]. It shares the {{IPA|[ɕʷ]}} and {{IPA|[ʑʷ]}} sounds with the [[Sadz dialect]], and the {{IPA|[t͡ɕ]}}, {{IPA|[d͡ʑ]}}, {{IPA|[t͡ɕʼ]}}, {{IPA|[ɕ]}}, {{IPA|[ʑ]}}, {{IPA|[χˤ]}}, and {{IPA|[χˤʷ]}} sounds are unique to Bzyb. Standard Abkhaz (which is based on the [[Abzhywa dialect]]) lacks these sounds.
The Bzyb [[consonant]] inventory appears to have been the fundamental inventory of [[Proto-Abkhaz]], with the inventories of Abzhywa and Sadz being reduced from this total, rather than the Bzyb series being innovative.
